    id: 14,
    level: 'elementary',
    topic: 'Government Services',
    title: 'Going to the DMV',
    passage: `The Department of Motor Vehicles, commonly known as the DMV, is a government office that handles driver's licenses, vehicle registration, and other road-related documents. For many immigrants in America, visiting the DMV for the first time can be a confusing and stressful experience. I know this because my first visit was not easy.

I needed to get a state ID card. Even if you do not drive, a state ID is very useful in America. It serves as official identification and is accepted almost everywhere — at banks, airports, government offices, and even when buying alcohol at a store. Without a state ID or driver's license, proving your identity in daily life can be difficult.

Before going to the DMV, I researched what documents I needed. The requirements vary depending on what you are applying for, but for a state ID, I needed proof of identity, proof of Social Security Number, and two documents showing proof of address. Acceptable documents for proof of address included utility bills, bank statements, and lease agreements. I gathered everything carefully and put it in a folder.

I made an appointment online. The DMV also accepts walk-ins, but appointments are faster. My appointment was at nine in the morning on a Wednesday. When I arrived, the waiting room was already full of people. I checked in at a machine near the entrance — I typed in my appointment confirmation number and received a paper ticket with a number on it.

I sat and waited for my number to be called. The waiting room had many chairs, and a large screen on the wall displayed which numbers were being served. After about twenty-five minutes, my number appeared on the screen. I went to the window.

The DMV officer was professional but serious. She checked each of my documents carefully. She asked me to verify my name, address, and Social Security Number. Everything was in order. She took my photo and asked me to look straight at the camera. She also asked me to read some letters on a vision chart to check my eyesight.

The ID card would not be ready that day. She told me it would arrive by mail within two to three weeks. She gave me a temporary paper ID to use in the meantime.

When I left the DMV, I felt relieved and proud. Getting a state ID was a small but important step in building my life in America. It made me feel more official — like I truly belonged here.`,
