    id: 15,
    level: 'elementary',
    topic: 'Education & Community',
    title: 'Using Public Libraries',
    passage: `Before I came to America, I thought libraries were only places where people went to borrow books. I was surprised to discover how much more public libraries offer in the United States. American public libraries are extraordinary community resources that provide a wide range of free services to everyone — including immigrants and newcomers.

The first library I visited was the Central Branch of the Seattle Public Library. It was a beautiful modern building with large glass walls. When I walked in, I was immediately struck by how quiet and calm it was. There were rows and rows of bookshelves, comfortable seating areas, and several computer stations where people were working or browsing the internet.

I approached the information desk and spoke to a librarian named Ms. Patel. She was very welcoming and asked how she could help. I explained that I was new to the area and wanted to get a library card. She smiled and said, "You've come to the right place."

Getting a library card was simple and completely free. I just needed to show my ID and proof of address. Ms. Patel took my information, typed it into the computer, and printed a library card for me on the spot. The whole process took less than five minutes.

With my library card, I could borrow up to twenty-five books at a time for three weeks. If I needed more time, I could renew them online, by phone, or in person — as long as no one else had requested the same book. I could also borrow DVDs, audiobooks, and magazines.

But what surprised me most was the range of other services. The library offered free English classes for immigrants every Tuesday and Thursday evening. There were also free computer classes for beginners, job search assistance, and help with filling out government forms. Every month, there was a free cultural event — sometimes a film screening, sometimes a cooking demonstration, sometimes a talk by a local author.

Ms. Patel also told me about the library's digital services. With my library card number, I could access thousands of e-books and audiobooks for free through an app on my phone. I could also access online learning platforms and databases of newspapers and academic journals.

I left the library that day with a bag full of books, a library card, and a schedule of upcoming events. The public library became one of my favorite places in Seattle. It was a place where I could learn, grow, and feel connected to my new community — all for free.`,
