    id: 22,
    level: 'intermediate',
    topic: 'Health & Wellbeing',
    title: 'How Sleep Affects Your Health',
    passage: `Sleep is one of the most fundamental biological needs of the human body, yet it is one of the most frequently sacrificed in modern life. Across the world, millions of people consistently get less sleep than they need, often treating sleep as a luxury rather than a necessity. Research in sleep science has made it increasingly clear that this is a serious mistake — one with profound consequences for physical health, mental wellbeing, cognitive performance, and even social relationships.

The human body goes through several distinct stages of sleep during each night. The two main categories are non-REM sleep and REM sleep. Non-REM sleep consists of three stages, ranging from light sleep — where you can be easily woken — to deep sleep, also called slow-wave sleep, where the body does most of its physical repair work. During deep sleep, the body releases growth hormones, repairs damaged tissues, strengthens the immune system, and consolidates physical memories such as motor skills. REM sleep, which stands for Rapid Eye Movement, is the stage most associated with dreaming. During REM sleep, the brain processes emotional experiences, consolidates memories, and makes creative connections between ideas. A healthy night of sleep cycles through these stages multiple times, with REM periods becoming longer towards the morning.

Most adults need between seven and nine hours of sleep per night to function optimally. However, research shows that a significant proportion of adults regularly sleep fewer than six hours. The consequences of this are far-reaching. In the short term, sleep deprivation impairs concentration, reaction time, decision-making, and emotional regulation. A person who has slept only five hours is cognitively impaired in ways that are comparable to someone who is legally drunk — yet most sleep-deprived people are unaware of just how impaired they are, because tiredness itself reduces your ability to accurately assess your own performance.

In the long term, chronic sleep deprivation has been linked to a wide range of serious health conditions. These include obesity — partly because poor sleep disrupts hormones that regulate hunger and satiety, causing people to eat more and crave high-calorie foods. It is also associated with an increased risk of type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease, hypertension, and weakened immunity. Studies have found that people who consistently sleep less than six hours per night have significantly higher rates of these conditions compared to those who get adequate sleep. Additionally, poor sleep is strongly linked to mental health disorders, including depression and anxiety. The relationship is bidirectional — poor sleep worsens mental health, and poor mental health further disrupts sleep, creating a damaging cycle.

Despite this evidence, many people struggle to get enough sleep due to a combination of lifestyle factors and genuine sleep disorders. Common lifestyle factors include irregular sleep schedules — particularly the habit of staying up late on weekends and then trying to return to an earlier schedule on weekdays, a pattern sometimes called "social jetlag." Excessive use of electronic devices before bed is another major factor. Screens emit blue light, which suppresses the production of melatonin — the hormone that signals to your body that it is time to sleep. Stress and anxiety are also major disruptors, as an overactive mind makes it difficult to fall and stay asleep.

Sleep hygiene refers to the set of habits and practices that promote consistent, high-quality sleep. Key principles of good sleep hygiene include maintaining a consistent sleep and wake time every day — even on weekends — creating a cool, dark, and quiet sleeping environment, avoiding caffeine after midday, limiting alcohol in the evening, and reducing screen time in the hour before bed. Physical exercise also improves sleep quality, though exercising too close to bedtime can have the opposite effect for some people.

Understanding the science of sleep is not just an academic exercise. For anyone seeking to improve their health, productivity, mood, and quality of life, prioritising sleep is one of the highest-return investments they can make. As one prominent sleep researcher put it, sleep is not the foundation upon which good health rests — it is the foundation upon which everything else rests.`,
