    topic: 'Technology & Society',
    title: 'Social Media — Benefits and Risks',
    passage: `Social media has transformed the way human beings communicate, share information, form relationships, and understand the world. Platforms such as Facebook, Instagram, YouTube, TikTok, and X — formerly known as Twitter — have billions of active users globally. For many people, particularly younger generations, social media is not just a tool they use occasionally — it is a fundamental part of daily life, woven into their social identity, their access to information, and their sense of connection with others. Like most powerful technologies, social media brings genuine benefits alongside serious risks, and navigating it wisely requires understanding both sides clearly.

The benefits of social media are real and significant. For individuals, platforms provide unprecedented access to information, education, and communities that would otherwise be inaccessible. A young person in a rural area can learn from world-class educators, connect with others who share niche interests, and access opportunities that geography would previously have denied them. For businesses and creators, social media has democratised visibility — a small business owner can now reach thousands of potential customers without an advertising budget, and an artist can build a global audience from their bedroom. For social movements, platforms have proven to be powerful tools for organising, raising awareness, and holding powerful institutions accountable.

Social media also serves a genuine psychological function for many users — it provides a sense of connection, community, and belonging. For immigrants, people with disabilities, or individuals in isolated situations, online communities can be a lifeline that provides support, validation, and friendship that their immediate physical environment cannot offer. The ability to maintain relationships across great geographical distances has also been transformed — staying in touch with family and friends abroad is now effortless and free.

However, the risks associated with heavy social media use are equally real and well-documented. Perhaps the most thoroughly researched concern is its effect on mental health, particularly among young people. Numerous studies have found associations between heavy social media use and increased rates of anxiety, depression, loneliness, and low self-esteem. Researchers point to several mechanisms. First, social comparison — the tendency to measure your own life, appearance, and achievements against the carefully curated highlight reels of others — can generate feelings of inadequacy. Most people present an idealised version of themselves online, which creates a distorted picture of how others actually live.

Second, the algorithms that power social media platforms are designed not to show you what is most accurate or most beneficial to you, but what will keep you engaged for the longest time. This means content that provokes strong emotional reactions — outrage, fear, envy, excitement — is systematically amplified, because strong emotions drive engagement. As a result, users are often exposed to an exaggerated, polarised, and emotionally charged version of reality that can distort their worldview over time.

Third, the design of social media platforms exploits psychological vulnerabilities in ways that promote addictive behaviour. Features like infinite scroll, variable reward mechanisms — where you never quite know when you will receive a "like" or a positive comment, similar to a slot machine — and notification systems are deliberately engineered to maximise time spent on the platform. This can make social media genuinely difficult to use in moderation, even for people who recognise that excessive use is harming them.

The issue of misinformation is also a serious concern. False information spreads dramatically faster on social media than accurate information, partly because it tends to be more emotionally provocative and therefore more shareable. This has had real-world consequences — from health misinformation affecting vaccination rates to political disinformation influencing elections.

Using social media wisely requires deliberate strategy. Setting time limits, being selective about who you follow, regularly evaluating how you feel after using certain platforms, and cultivating a healthy scepticism toward sensational or emotionally charged content are all practical steps. Social media is neither universally good nor universally bad — it is a tool, and like all tools, its impact depends almost entirely on how it is used.`,
